China Powerplus, Eratat, Noble Group: Singapore Stocks Preview

-- B y   J o n a t h a n   B u r g o s
-- 
2011-04-07T00:08:09Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-07/china-powerplus-eratat-noble-group-singapore-stocks-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes in  Singapore  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and share prices are from the previous close.  Singapore’s Straits Times Index gained 0.8 percent to
3,170.33.  Commodity suppliers: The Thomson Reuters/Jefferies CRB
Index, which tracks prices of 19 commodities from copper to corn,
rose 0.1 percent in  New York  yesterday, extending its advance
for a fifth day.  Noble Group Ltd. (NOBL)  , a Hong Kong-based supplier of
commodities increased, 0.9 percent to S$2.23.  Olam International
Ltd. (OLAM)  , a Singapore-based supplier of agricultural
commodities, climbed 2.1 percent to S$2.89.  AA Group Holdings Ltd. (AAG)  : The supplier of components
used in the manufacture of audio devices said it has amended its
2010 financial statement to reflect a reduction in trade
receivables. The changes won’t have a material impact on the
group’s full-year results, it said. AA Group declined 10 percent
to 4.5 Singapore cents when it last traded in February.  China Powerplus Ltd. (CPOW)  : The maker of hand-held  farm
equipment  said it incurred a full-year loss of 20.2 million yuan
($3 million), instead of a profit of 57.7 million as reported on
March 1. The discrepancy was discovered following an audit,
which required the accounting of an impairment charge of 77.9
million yuan at an associate company, it said. The stock
declined 13 percent to 3.5 Singapore cents.  Eratat Lifestyle Ltd. (ERAT)  : The China-based maker of
athletic shoes and apparel said it will sell 45 million new
shares at 20.2 Singapore cents each, raising net proceeds of
S$8.8 million ($6.9 million). Eratat fell 2.2 percent to 22
Singapore cents when it last traded on April 5. It was suspended
from trading yesterday and will resume trading today.  HLH Group Ltd. (HLHG)  : The property developer and owner
of a corn plantation in Cambodia said it appointed Ong Bee Huat,
the company’s founder, as chief executive officer. HLH Group was
unchanged at 3 Singapore cents.  SIA Engineering Co. (SIE SP): The aircraft maintenance arm
of Singapore Airlines Ltd. (SIA SP) said it and a unit of Safran
SA (SAF FP) opened an avionics maintenance facility, which could
handle new aircraft models such Boeing B787 Dreamliner and the
Airbus A350, in Singapore. The stock gained 1.5 percent to
S$4.08.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Jonathan Burgos in Singapore at 
 jburgos4@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Nick Gentle at 
 ngentle2@bloomberg.net . 